track_notes:
Parking at the trailhead known as the Black Road (Galty way climb car park in google maps), follow the trail upwards until it peters out. Heading left, aim for the coll between Galtybeg and Galtymore, keeping up on the slope of Galtybeg to avoid boggy ground as best you can. Climb down from the peat hag and turn immediately right, heading north through the gap in the hags for the far side of the ridge, avoiding the apparently obvious direct route over the hags. There is a trail around the hags to the north with good views of the lake below. The track is on the edge, so care is needed. Follow this track and begin the climb the summit. There is no obvious or continuous trail to the summit. 
The summit is wide and open with some boulders to provide shelter for activation. There is good mobile signal at the summit. The trail is about 6K, the slope on the lower road is gentle, with a climb at the end to the summit.

This combines Cush and Galtymore in a loop from the North. Park at the Clydagh Bridge carpark. See route instructions for Cush. Once finished on Cush, continue South and descend to the coll between Cush and Galtybeg.Begin the ascent of Galtybeg. This is in two halves, the lower half being steeper. From Galtybeg summit you can see Galtymore. See other instructions for the Galtymore ascent. To return to the car park, continue west and descend to the wall. Follow this wall descending and as you slightly ascend, veer off to the east. The track is intermittent. The descent proper begins now and you end up on a grassy section just before you enter the woods. There are way post markers along this section. Once in the woords, follow the road and take the shortcut indicated bny the trailhead sign. Continue on over a bridge til you return to the car park.

Its about 14K in total, with 1100m of climbing. The climbs of Cush, Galtybeg and Galtymore are significant, so be prepared.
